262
00:09:27,827 --> 00:09:29,560
What?

263
00:09:29,595 --> 00:09:31,307
We've never even seen
your fundamental principles

264
00:09:31,331 --> 00:09:32,797
prior to applying
for that patent.

265
00:09:32,832 --> 00:09:34,365
Can you prove that?

266
00:09:34,400 --> 00:09:36,467
Of course we can't...
prove that.

267
00:09:36,502 --> 00:09:38,402
It's not possible
to prove a negative.

268
00:09:38,438 --> 00:09:41,038
Words spoken by every hack
who's ever copied

269
00:09:41,074 --> 00:09:44,342
someone else's technology
and claimed it as their own.

270
00:09:46,279 --> 00:09:48,579
What's going on here?

271
00:09:48,614 --> 00:09:51,248
I came to you to negotiate
an exclusion in good faith.

272
00:09:51,284 --> 00:09:52,983
And we're prepared
to offer you--

273
00:09:53,019 --> 00:09:54,819
We don't care
what you're prepared to offer.

274
00:09:54,854 --> 00:09:56,665
And we didn't bring you here
to give you an exclusion.

275
00:09:56,689 --> 00:09:58,322
We brought you here
to send a message.

276
00:09:58,358 --> 00:10:01,192
This is a $90 million lawsuit
against your client

277
00:10:01,227 --> 00:10:02,626
if they go to market.

278
00:10:05,898 --> 00:10:07,665
Gentlemen, please,

279
00:10:07,700 --> 00:10:10,267
I am not saying
we got here first.

280
00:10:10,303 --> 00:10:12,269
But it's a 2.5% overlap,

281
00:10:12,305 --> 00:10:15,106
and we are open to a 15%
revenue sharing arrangement.

282
00:10:15,141 --> 00:10:17,842
And we're not open to shit,
because we were here first.

283
00:10:17,877 --> 00:10:21,612
Listen to me.
I am trying to keep my cool.

284
00:10:21,647 --> 00:10:23,714
We don't care
if you keep your cool or not.

285
00:10:23,750 --> 00:10:25,082
Because we've got you,

286
00:10:25,118 --> 00:10:26,717
and there's nothing
you can do about it.

287
00:10:26,753 --> 00:10:28,297
So you can take your offer
and shove it in a drawer

288
00:10:28,321 --> 00:10:31,622
along with that sorry excuse
for a digital secretary,

289
00:10:31,657 --> 00:10:35,292
because neither one of them is
ever gonna see the light of day.

290
00:10:35,328 --> 00:10:38,295
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

291
00:10:38,331 --> 00:10:45,336
<i>♪ ♪</i>

292
00:10:47,774 --> 00:10:50,074
Oliver.
What are you doing?

293
00:10:50,109 --> 00:10:51,442
Is it still on?

294
00:10:51,477 --> 00:10:53,711
- Is what still on?
- Your deal.

295
00:10:53,746 --> 00:10:55,546
To get into the Bar.

296
00:10:55,581 --> 00:10:56,947
Oliver, listen to me.

297
00:10:56,983 --> 00:10:58,660
Because when I asked Nathan
where you were,

298
00:10:58,684 --> 00:11:00,763
he said you were taking a couple
days for personal reasons.

299
00:11:00,787 --> 00:11:02,164
And all of a sudden,
I got this pit in my stomach

300
00:11:02,188 --> 00:11:04,054
that wouldn't go away.

301
00:11:04,090 --> 00:11:06,557
So I decided to ask you if
there's a reason I got that pit

302
00:11:06,592 --> 00:11:08,759
or if I'm just an asshole
for doubting you.

303
00:11:10,530 --> 00:11:11,862
You're not an asshole,
Oliver.

304
00:11:11,898 --> 00:11:13,564
God damn it, Mike!

305
00:11:13,599 --> 00:11:14,777
You told me
you didn't have to tell Nathan

306
00:11:14,801 --> 00:11:16,333
because there was
nothing to tell.

307
00:11:16,369 --> 00:11:17,902
And when I told you that,
there wasn't.

308
00:11:17,937 --> 00:11:19,703
But then my deal
got put back on the table.

309
00:11:19,739 --> 00:11:21,705
Which means you could have
told him this morning.

310
00:11:21,741 --> 00:11:24,608
But you didn't,
so now I have to.

311
00:11:24,644 --> 00:11:26,121
Oliver, hey, wait!
Please, hear me out!

312
00:11:26,145 --> 00:11:27,945
I'm not gonna
hear you out, Mike.

313
00:11:27,980 --> 00:11:31,115
I was sitting here for an hour,
hoping I was wrong about you.

314
00:11:31,150 --> 00:11:33,350
You weren't wrong about me.

315
00:11:33,386 --> 00:11:36,220
I care about people.
I want to help the clinic.

316
00:11:36,255 --> 00:11:38,289
And the reason I didn't tell
Nathan what I did

317
00:11:38,324 --> 00:11:40,302
is because I'm just waiting
until I can help him even more.

318
00:11:40,326 --> 00:11:42,293
Help how?
By being a shady lawyer?

319
00:11:42,328 --> 00:11:44,829
By being someone who wouldn't
have lost Sofia Price her home.

320
00:11:46,732 --> 00:11:48,732
I cannot believe
you just said that to me.

321
00:11:48,768 --> 00:11:52,336
I said it because it's true,
and you know it.

322
00:11:53,739 --> 00:11:56,540
Look, I am gonna
tell Nathan everything

323
00:11:56,576 --> 00:11:58,843
as soon as my hearing is over.
You have my word.

324
00:11:58,878 --> 00:12:00,744
Why should I believe
the word of a liar?

325
00:12:00,780 --> 00:12:03,247
Because of what I did
for those miners and the clinic.

326
00:12:03,282 --> 00:12:05,683
And if that's not enough,
how about what I did for you?

327
00:12:05,718 --> 00:12:09,019
You didn't do shit for me.
But fine, I won't tell Nathan.

328
00:12:09,055 --> 00:12:10,754
Just so long as
when this thing's over,

329
00:12:10,790 --> 00:12:12,656
you go back
to your corrupt corporate world.

330
00:12:12,692 --> 00:12:14,925
Because I don't care
what you tell yourself.

331
00:12:14,961 --> 00:12:18,696
You're never
gonna belong in mine.

332
00:12:18,731 --> 00:12:22,900
<i>[tense music]</i>

333
00:12:25,493 --> 00:12:27,423
Harvey, what are
you still doing here?

334
00:12:27,424 --> 00:12:29,257
The hearing's across town
in ten minutes.

335
00:12:29,292 --> 00:12:31,204
I'm not going to the hearing,
Donna, and neither are you.

336
00:12:31,228 --> 00:12:32,994
- Why not?
- Because if you and I can't do

337
00:12:33,030 --> 00:12:35,208
what we need to, then whatever
Mike does at that hearing

338
00:12:35,232 --> 00:12:36,998
isn't gonna matter.
Give it to me.

339
00:12:37,034 --> 00:12:39,212
We need to figure out what
Walter Samson's weak spot is.

340
00:12:39,236 --> 00:12:40,702
Tell me how, and I'm all in.

341
00:12:40,737 --> 00:12:42,570
Start by contacting
every person we know

342
00:12:42,606 --> 00:12:44,572
and asking them what they know
about this asshole.

343
00:12:44,608 --> 00:12:46,608
Because Gibbs
has something on him

344
00:12:46,643 --> 00:12:48,009
and if I can't find out
what it is,

345
00:12:48,045 --> 00:12:50,612
then I can't get her
off that committee.

346
00:12:50,647 --> 00:12:52,247
Where are you going?

347
00:12:52,282 --> 00:12:55,550
To see someone
who doesn't know Samson at all.

348
00:12:57,054 --> 00:12:59,487
Before we get started,
I'd like to point out

349
00:12:59,523 --> 00:13:01,667
these interviews are normally
for us to quickly approve

350
00:13:01,691 --> 00:13:03,158
standard applicants to the Bar.

351
00:13:03,193 --> 00:13:05,527
However, Mr. Ross
is no standard applicant.

352
00:13:05,562 --> 00:13:07,829
Therefore, we will convene
for as long as it takes

353
00:13:07,864 --> 00:13:10,565
before ruling
on his application.

354
00:13:10,600 --> 00:13:12,667
Now...
Mr. Chairman, if I may.

355
00:13:12,702 --> 00:13:15,537
Last winter,
Mr. Ross pled guilty

356
00:13:15,572 --> 00:13:17,672
to defrauding
the citizens of New York.

357
00:13:17,707 --> 00:13:20,642
Therefore, I propose we reject
his application right now

358
00:13:20,677 --> 00:13:22,310
because Mr. Ross is a felon

359
00:13:22,345 --> 00:13:24,913
and the New York Bar
does not accept felons.

360
00:13:24,948 --> 00:13:27,260
Mr. Chairman, with all due
respect to the new board member,

361
00:13:27,284 --> 00:13:28,850
you do.

362
00:13:28,885 --> 00:13:30,919
Not only does the Bar
accept felons, but years ago,

363
00:13:30,954 --> 00:13:34,055
this very committee
admitted Neal Wiesner,

364
00:13:34,091 --> 00:13:37,080
a man who spent years in prison
for attempted murder.

365
00:13:37,081 --> 00:13:39,014
Now, Ms. Gibbs may think
my crime is worse

366
00:13:39,048 --> 00:13:40,848
than attempted murder,
but I don't think

367
00:13:40,883 --> 00:13:42,661
it's worth throwing away
140 years of precedent

368
00:13:42,685 --> 00:13:45,019
by not even allowing me
to make my case.

369
00:13:45,054 --> 00:13:47,722
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

370
00:13:47,757 --> 00:13:54,362
<i>♪ ♪</i>

371
00:13:54,397 --> 00:13:56,030
Come on, let's go.

372
00:13:56,065 --> 00:13:58,799
- What the hell are you doing?
- What does it look like

373
00:13:58,835 --> 00:14:00,679
I'm doing? I'm watching my money
go down the toilet.

374
00:14:00,703 --> 00:14:03,170
Well, it looks to me
like I paid you to do a job,

375
00:14:03,206 --> 00:14:04,672
and you're sitting here
doing this.

376
00:14:04,707 --> 00:14:06,641
Okay, I'll let you in
on a little secret.

377
00:14:06,676 --> 00:14:08,843
It only takes 15 minutes
to hack someone.

378
00:14:08,878 --> 00:14:10,678
If you can't find something
in the next 45,

379
00:14:10,713 --> 00:14:12,280
it means
there's nothing to find.

380
00:14:12,315 --> 00:14:14,048
Bullshit. There's always
something to find.

381
00:14:14,083 --> 00:14:15,816
I'm telling you,
there isn't.

382
00:14:15,852 --> 00:14:17,852
He doesn't drink, smoke,
gamble, cheat, nothing.

383
00:14:17,887 --> 00:14:20,521
Listen to me. I paid you
good money to do a job,

384
00:14:20,556 --> 00:14:22,368
and if you don't put
some more effort into this,

385
00:14:22,392 --> 00:14:24,692
I'm gonna spread the word
that you aren't worth shit.

386
00:14:24,727 --> 00:14:26,727
And this time it won't
be coming from Louis Litt.

387
00:14:26,763 --> 00:14:28,863
It'll be coming from me.
Then keep your damn money.

388
00:14:28,898 --> 00:14:30,309
When I tell you
there's nothing to find,

389
00:14:30,333 --> 00:14:32,700
there's nothing to find.

390
00:14:32,735 --> 00:14:37,505
I guess what I'm saying is
not only do I admit what I did,

391
00:14:37,540 --> 00:14:41,075
but...I regret it

392
00:14:41,110 --> 00:14:44,712
with every fiber of my being.

393
00:14:44,747 --> 00:14:47,848
And I'd like to apologize
to my clients,

394
00:14:47,884 --> 00:14:50,751
my former colleagues,
and finally to the fraternity

395
00:14:50,787 --> 00:14:53,721
of men and woman that
I've wanted to be a member of

396
00:14:53,756 --> 00:14:55,956
since I was a child.

397
00:14:59,629 --> 00:15:01,529
Well, that was
a moving statement.

398
00:15:01,564 --> 00:15:02,997
I just have one question.

399
00:15:03,032 --> 00:15:04,765
If you regret
what you did so much,

400
00:15:04,801 --> 00:15:06,934
why weren't you willing
to serve your full sentence?

401
00:15:06,969 --> 00:15:09,770
Well, I wasn't unwilling.
I was offered a deal

402
00:15:09,806 --> 00:15:12,139
to help convict a known
criminal, and I took it.

403
00:15:12,175 --> 00:15:13,808
You were offered a deal
to get out early,

404
00:15:13,843 --> 00:15:16,043
and you took it.
I protected an innocent man--

405
00:15:16,079 --> 00:15:18,145
What you did
was insinuate yourself

406
00:15:18,181 --> 00:15:19,792
into your roommate's life,
gain his trust,

407
00:15:19,816 --> 00:15:22,850
and pretend to be his friend.
True or false?

408
00:15:22,885 --> 00:15:24,719
[scoffs]

409
00:15:24,754 --> 00:15:26,187
You're taking it out of context.

410
00:15:26,222 --> 00:15:27,988
The context is
you portrayed yourself

411
00:15:28,024 --> 00:15:30,157
as one thing
when, really, you were another,

412
00:15:30,193 --> 00:15:31,570
which is what you did
the entire time

413
00:15:31,594 --> 00:15:33,160
you pretended to be an attorney

414
00:15:33,196 --> 00:15:36,664
and what I believe you are doing
to this body right now.

415
00:15:36,699 --> 00:15:39,734
Mr. Chairmen, if she's going
to impugn his character

416
00:15:39,769 --> 00:15:41,869
while he's speaking,
then he's entitled

417
00:15:41,904 --> 00:15:43,304
to let someone else
speak for him.

418
00:15:43,339 --> 00:15:44,772
This isn't
a trial.

419
00:15:44,807 --> 00:15:46,118
We don't allow
character witnesses here.

420
00:15:46,142 --> 00:15:47,108
Actually, you do.

421
00:15:47,143 --> 00:15:49,377
Article 4, 16A.

422
00:15:49,412 --> 00:15:51,812
Applicants are allowed
a witness as a rebuttal

423
00:15:51,848 --> 00:15:54,815
for an accusation leveled
by a committee member.

424
00:15:54,851 --> 00:15:56,984
That article hasn't been cited
in 30 years.

425
00:15:57,019 --> 00:15:59,487
Maybe that's because no
applicant has ever had to stand

426
00:15:59,522 --> 00:16:01,622
before the person
who put them away.

427
00:16:01,657 --> 00:16:03,190
You make a point.

428
00:16:03,226 --> 00:16:04,503
We'll pick this up
first thing in the morning

429
00:16:04,527 --> 00:16:06,127
with your witness.
Thank you.

430
00:16:11,300 --> 00:16:13,334
Rachel, that was exactly
what I needed.

431
00:16:13,369 --> 00:16:14,869
If you hadn't done that--
I know.

432
00:16:14,904 --> 00:16:16,315
But right now I'm more
concerned with the fact

433
00:16:16,339 --> 00:16:17,683
that she's turning them
against you.

434
00:16:17,707 --> 00:16:20,441
Which means even after
Harvey kicks her off,

435
00:16:20,476 --> 00:16:23,477
Seidel's job is gonna be
that much harder.

436
00:16:23,513 --> 00:16:26,347
And we only have one shot
at having someone speak for me.

437
00:16:26,382 --> 00:16:28,616
Mike, come on.
We gotta get back to the office

438
00:16:28,651 --> 00:16:30,551
and start going through
everyone it could be.

439
00:16:30,586 --> 00:16:31,864
We'll make a list
of pros and cons.

440
00:16:31,888 --> 00:16:35,856
Rachel...
I know who it is.

441
00:16:35,892 --> 00:16:38,859
<i>[tense music]</i>

442
00:16:38,895 --> 00:16:45,032
<i>♪ ♪</i>

443
00:16:45,067 --> 00:16:47,034
Julius.

444
00:16:47,069 --> 00:16:50,838
Mike.
What are you doing here?

445
00:16:50,873 --> 00:16:52,673
I was hoping
we could talk.

446
00:16:52,708 --> 00:16:55,342
Uh, look, I'm sorry, man.
This is not a good time.

447
00:16:55,378 --> 00:16:56,855
I just put the baby down
and the wife and I--

448
00:16:56,879 --> 00:16:58,612
Please, it won't take long.

449
00:16:58,648 --> 00:16:59,847
I got this hearing tomorrow

450
00:16:59,882 --> 00:17:02,082
for the Character portion
of the Bar,

451
00:17:02,118 --> 00:17:04,752
and I wanted to ask
if you'd speak for me.

452
00:17:04,787 --> 00:17:06,687
You mind if I ask, why me?

453
00:17:06,722 --> 00:17:08,756
Because you're the only one
I know who's qualified

454
00:17:08,791 --> 00:17:10,202
to tell the board
that I was a different man

455
00:17:10,226 --> 00:17:13,093
when I got out
than when I went in.

456
00:17:13,129 --> 00:17:15,329
No offense, Mike...

457
00:17:15,364 --> 00:17:17,932
but the truth is,
I'm not sure you are.

458
00:17:17,967 --> 00:17:19,366
What do you mean?

459
00:17:19,402 --> 00:17:20,813
I mean you said
this hearing is tomorrow.

460
00:17:20,837 --> 00:17:22,136
But you're just now
coming to me,

461
00:17:22,171 --> 00:17:24,205
which means
something's going on.

462
00:17:24,240 --> 00:17:25,973
What's going on is the woman
who put me away

463
00:17:26,008 --> 00:17:27,608
managed to get herself
on the committee,

464
00:17:27,643 --> 00:17:29,221
and now she's slamming
the door in my face.

465
00:17:29,245 --> 00:17:30,811
- And why would she do that?
- Julius--

466
00:17:30,847 --> 00:17:32,613
Mike, how did you even
get a hearing?

467
00:17:32,648 --> 00:17:34,982
What are you talking about?
I applied, like everyone else.

468
00:17:35,017 --> 00:17:36,817
No, you're not
like everyone else.

469
00:17:36,853 --> 00:17:38,719
You didn't go to law school.
It doesn't matter.

470
00:17:38,754 --> 00:17:40,232
There's an exception
called "reading the law."

471
00:17:40,256 --> 00:17:41,689
See, right there, Mike,

472
00:17:41,724 --> 00:17:44,024
that sounds like the bullshit
artist I met in prison.

473
00:17:44,060 --> 00:17:45,693
So you tell me right now.

474
00:17:45,728 --> 00:17:49,730
Did you pull some shit
to make this happen?

475
00:17:49,765 --> 00:17:51,966
Damn, Mike, if you can't
be straight with me,

476
00:17:52,001 --> 00:17:54,368
this conversation
ends right here.

477
00:17:54,403 --> 00:17:57,137
Yes, I did.

478
00:17:57,173 --> 00:17:59,940
Ah, finally.

479
00:17:59,976 --> 00:18:01,842
Some truth in the night.

480
00:18:01,878 --> 00:18:05,479
Julius, I work at a law
clinic, but not as a lawyer.

481
00:18:05,515 --> 00:18:07,781
An opportunity presented itself
for me to become one

482
00:18:07,817 --> 00:18:09,783
and I turned it down,
but then I had to sit there

483
00:18:09,819 --> 00:18:11,585
and watch a woman
get put on the street

484
00:18:11,621 --> 00:18:13,454
because I couldn't help her.

485
00:18:13,489 --> 00:18:15,155
And I knew I'd have to
